## file.bridge — bidirectional .md file communication between ThinkDrop and Windsurf/Cursor/any tool

Use `file.bridge` to **pass instructions, results, and context between ThinkDrop AI and external tools** (Windsurf, Cursor, Warp, another AI agent) via a shared Markdown file. Both sides write structured comment blocks that are invisible in rendered Markdown but parseable by the skill.

**Default bridge file:** `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md`

**Protocol — block format in the .md file:**
```
<!-- TD:INSTRUCTION id=td_instruction_abc123 ts=2026-02-24T17:00:00Z status=pending -->
Refactor the login component to use the new auth hook
<!-- TD:END -->

<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_def456 ref=td_instruction_abc123 ts=2026-02-24T17:01:00Z status=done -->
Done — refactored LoginForm.tsx, updated 3 files
<!-- WS:END -->
```
- **`TD:` blocks** — written by ThinkDrop AI
- **`WS:` blocks** — written by Windsurf/Cursor/external agent (Windsurf can be configured to watch and respond to this file)

**CRITICAL action decision rules — always follow these exactly:**
- "check the bridge" / "any ThinkDrop instructions?" / "what did ThinkDrop send?" / "check for instructions" → `action: "read"` (reads ALL blocks) + `synthesize` to summarize. **NEVER use `status` for this. NEVER add a `file.bridge write` step for read-only bridge checks — only display the content, do NOT write anything back.**
- "act on the bridge" / "execute bridge instructions" / "do what the bridge says" / "run the bridge task" → `action: "read"` to get pending blocks, then execute each pending `WS:INSTRUCTION` block's body as a task (use `fs.read`, `shell.run`, `browser.act`, etc.), then `file.bridge write` with `prefix: "TD"`, `blockType: "RESULT"`, `status: "done"` to write the result back.
- `file.bridge act` followed by an instruction body (sent by the bridge auto-listener in ThinkDrop) → parse the instruction from the message body, execute it directly (do NOT call file.bridge read first — the instruction is already in the message), then `file.bridge write` with `prefix: "TD"`, `blockType: "RESULT"`, `status: "done"`, `refId: "<block id from message>"` to write the result back. **Extract the block id from the line `Block ID: <id>` in the message.**
- "read what Windsurf wrote" / "what did Windsurf respond?" / "check WS responses" → `action: "read"`, `filterPrefix: "WS"` + `synthesize`
- "write to Windsurf" / "tell Windsurf to X" / "send instruction to Windsurf" → `action: "write"`, `message: "<the instruction>"`
- "wait for Windsurf to respond" / "poll for response" → `action: "poll"`, `filterPrefix: "WS"`
- "bridge status" / "how many blocks" / "is the bridge set up?" → `action: "status"` (metadata only, no content)
- "clear the bridge" / "reset the bridge" → `action: "clear"`
- "set up the bridge" / "init the bridge" → `action: "init"`

**Actions:**
- `init` — create/reset the bridge file with a header (run once to set up)
- `write` — append a `TD:` instruction or result block
- `read` — read and parse all blocks, returns full block content including bodies. Use this for "check the bridge".
- `poll` — wait for a `WS:` response block to appear (blocks until response or timeout)
- `clear` — remove all blocks (or only TD/WS blocks)
- `status` — metadata only (block counts, file size, last modified). Does NOT return block content. Do NOT use for "check the bridge".

**Args:**
- `action` — required. One of: `init` | `write` | `read` | `poll` | `clear` | `status`
- `message` — body text to write (for `write`)
- `bridgeFile` — custom path (default: `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md`)
- `prefix` — block prefix to write: `'TD'` (default) or custom
- `blockType` — block type label: `'INSTRUCTION'` | `'RESULT'` | `'QUESTION'` (default `'INSTRUCTION'`)
- `status` — status tag on the block: `'pending'` | `'done'` | `'error'` | `'info'`
- `refId` — ID of a prior block this is responding to
- `filterPrefix` — for `read`/`poll`: only return blocks with this prefix (e.g. `'WS'`)
- `pollTimeoutMs` — for `poll`: max ms to wait (default 120000 = 2 min)
- `sinceTs` — for `poll`/`read`: only return blocks after this ISO timestamp
- `label` — channel label shown in `status` and `init` header

**Typical pattern — ThinkDrop sends instruction, waits for Windsurf to respond:**
```
file.bridge write → file.bridge poll → synthesize on response
```

**Example — "check the bridge" / "any ThinkDrop instructions?" / "what did Windsurf send?":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "read" }, "description": "Read all blocks from the bridge file" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Summarize all blocks in the bridge file. List any pending TD: instructions and any WS: responses. Show the body content of each block." }, "description": "Summarize bridge contents" }
]
```

**Example — "act on the bridge" / "execute bridge instructions" / "do what the bridge says":**
Read pending WS: blocks, execute their task, write TD:RESULT back with the answer.
```json
[
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "read", "filterPrefix": "WS", "filterStatus": "pending" }, "description": "Read pending WS instructions from bridge" },
  { "skill": "fs.read", "args": { "action": "read", "path": "src/renderer/App.tsx" }, "description": "Execute the pending instruction — read App.tsx" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Based on the file content, provide a 2-sentence summary of what App.tsx does." }, "description": "Summarize App.tsx as requested" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "write", "message": "{{synthesisAnswer}}", "prefix": "TD", "blockType": "RESULT", "status": "done" }, "description": "Write result back to bridge for Windsurf" }
]
```

**Example — bridge instruction is a web search (e.g. "search Perplexity for X and write result back"):**
ALWAYS use `synthesize` to extract the page content, then pass `{{synthesisAnswer}}` as the `message` — NEVER write a URL or description string as the message.
```json
[
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "read", "filterPrefix": "WS", "filterStatus": "pending" }, "description": "Read pending WS instructions" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "navigate", "url": "https://www.perplexity.ai", "sessionId": "s1" }, "description": "Open Perplexity" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "smartType", "text": "best vegan food{ENTER}", "sessionId": "s1" }, "description": "Search for the query" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "waitForContent", "sessionId": "s1", "minLength": 1500, "timeoutMs": 60000 }, "description": "Wait for response" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "getPageText", "sessionId": "s1", "maxChars": 4000 }, "description": "Capture page content" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Extract and summarize the search results for 'best vegan food' from the page text." }, "description": "Summarize results" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "write", "message": "{{synthesisAnswer}}", "prefix": "TD", "blockType": "RESULT", "status": "done", "refId": "<block id from WS instruction>" }, "description": "Write result back to bridge" }
]
```

**Example — "Tell Windsurf to refactor the login component and wait for confirmation":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "init", "label": "ThinkDrop ↔ Windsurf" }, "description": "Initialize bridge file" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "write", "message": "Please refactor `src/components/LoginForm.tsx` to use the new `useAuth` hook from `src/hooks/useAuth.ts`. Replace all `useState` auth logic with the hook.", "blockType": "INSTRUCTION", "status": "pending" }, "description": "Write instruction for Windsurf" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "poll", "filterPrefix": "WS", "pollTimeoutMs": 300000 }, "description": "Wait up to 5 minutes for Windsurf to respond" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Windsurf responded to our refactor request. Summarize what was done based on the response block content." }, "description": "Summarize Windsurf's response" }
]
```

**Example — "Send ThinkDrop's analysis to Windsurf as context for a task":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "fs.read", "args": { "action": "explore", "path": "~/Desktop/projects/myapp" }, "description": "Read and understand the codebase" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Based on the codebase exploration, write a concise technical brief: what this app does, its tech stack, and the 3 most important areas that need attention." }, "description": "Draft technical brief" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "write", "message": "{{synthesisAnswer}}", "blockType": "RESULT", "status": "info" }, "description": "Write analysis to bridge file for Windsurf" }
]
```

**Example — "Read what Windsurf has written to the bridge file":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "read", "filterPrefix": "WS" }, "description": "Read all Windsurf responses from bridge file" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Based on the Windsurf response blocks, what has been completed and what is still pending?" }, "description": "Summarize Windsurf activity" }
]
```

**Example — "Post Jira comment when Windsurf completes work (file-triggered workflow)":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "poll", "filterPrefix": "WS", "filterStatus": "done", "pollTimeoutMs": 600000 }, "description": "Wait for Windsurf to mark a task done" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "navigate", "url": "https://your-org.atlassian.net", "sessionId": "jira1" }, "description": "Open Jira" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Write a Jira comment: 'Implementation complete — Windsurf finished the task. See bridge.md for details.'" }, "description": "Draft Jira comment" }
]
```

**Example — "Create a GitHub pull request for a branch":**
IMPORTANT rules for GitHub PR automation:
- **NEVER use `git checkout -b <branch>`** if the branch may already exist — use `git checkout <branch> 2>/dev/null || git checkout -b <branch>` to safely switch-or-create.
- **NEVER use `browser.act` to create GitHub PRs.** The `browser.act` browser has NO GitHub login session — it will hit the unauthenticated GitHub page and get stuck trying to find form fields. Use the **GitHub REST API via `shell.run curl`** instead.
- Retrieve the GitHub token from macOS keychain with: `security find-internet-password -s github.com -w`
- Use the token in a `curl` POST to `https://api.github.com/repos/<owner>/<repo>/pulls`
```json
[
  { "skill": "shell.run", "args": { "cmd": "bash", "argv": ["-c", "cd ~/Desktop/projects/myrepo && git checkout my-feature 2>/dev/null || git checkout -b my-feature && git add -A && git commit -m 'feat: my changes' --allow-empty && git push -u origin my-feature"] }, "description": "Switch to branch (or create it), commit, push" },
  { "skill": "shell.run", "args": { "cmd": "bash", "argv": ["-c", "TOKEN=$(security find-internet-password -s github.com -w 2>/dev/null | head -1) && curl -s -X POST -H \"Authorization: token $TOKEN\" -H \"Accept: application/vnd.github.v3+json\" https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/pulls -d '{\"title\":\"feat: my PR title\",\"body\":\"## Summary\\nDescription of changes.\",\"head\":\"my-feature\",\"base\":\"main\"}' | python3 -c \"import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d.get('html_url', d.get('message','error')))\""] }, "description": "Create PR via GitHub REST API using keychain token, print PR URL" }
]
```
The second `shell.run` prints the new PR URL (e.g. `https://github.com/owner/repo/pull/42`) or an error message if auth failed.

**Example — "Review a GitHub PR and post a comment":**
- Use `shell.run curl` to fetch PR files/diff and post the comment — **NEVER `browser.act`**
- GitHub Issues API is used for PR comments (PRs are issues): `POST /repos/<owner>/<repo>/issues/<number>/comments`
```json
[
  { "skill": "shell.run", "args": { "cmd": "bash", "argv": ["-c", "TOKEN=$(security find-internet-password -s github.com -w 2>/dev/null | head -1) && curl -s -H \"Authorization: token $TOKEN\" -H \"Accept: application/vnd.github.v3+json\" https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/pulls/42/files | python3 -c \"import sys,json; files=json.load(sys.stdin); [print(f['filename'], f.get('status','')) for f in files]\""] }, "description": "Fetch list of changed files in PR" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Based on the changed files listed, write a short PR review comment. If everything looks good, say 'This PR looks good to me. Changes are clean and well-scoped.'" }, "description": "Draft review comment" },
  { "skill": "shell.run", "args": { "cmd": "bash", "argv": ["-c", "TOKEN=$(security find-internet-password -s github.com -w 2>/dev/null | head -1) && COMMENT=$(cat /var/folders/$(ls /var/folders/ | head -1)/*/T/thinkdrop_synthesis_*.txt 2>/dev/null | tail -1 || echo 'This PR looks good to me.') && curl -s -X POST -H \"Authorization: token $TOKEN\" -H \"Accept: application/vnd.github.v3+json\" https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/issues/42/comments -d \"{\\\"body\\\":\\\"$COMMENT\\\"}\" | python3 -c \"import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d.get('html_url', d.get('message', str(d))))\""] }, "description": "Post comment on PR via GitHub API" }
]
```
**Simpler pattern** — use `{{synthesisAnswer}}` from a prior synthesize step directly in the shell command is not possible, so instead pass the comment text inline:
```json
[
  { "skill": "shell.run", "args": { "cmd": "bash", "argv": ["-c", "TOKEN=$(security find-internet-password -s github.com -w 2>/dev/null | head -1) && curl -s -H \"Authorization: token $TOKEN\" -H \"Accept: application/vnd.github.v3+json\" https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/pulls/42/files | python3 -c \"import sys,json; files=json.load(sys.stdin); print('Changed files: ' + ', '.join(f['filename'] for f in files))\""] }, "description": "Fetch PR changed files" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Write a one-sentence PR review comment based on these changed files. Be concise and positive if no issues found. Output ONLY the comment text, nothing else." }, "description": "Draft comment text" },
  { "skill": "shell.run", "args": { "cmd": "bash", "argv": ["-c", "TOKEN=$(security find-internet-password -s github.com -w 2>/dev/null | head -1) && curl -s -X POST -H \"Authorization: token $TOKEN\" -H \"Accept: application/vnd.github.v3+json\" https://api.github.com/repos/owner/repo/issues/42/comments -d '{\"body\":\"This PR looks good to me. Changes are clean and well-scoped.\"}' | python3 -c \"import sys,json; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(d.get('html_url', d.get('message', str(d))))\""] }, "description": "Post review comment via GitHub API" }
]
```

**Note on `file.bridge watch/listen`:** The bridge listener runs automatically inside ThinkDrop — it watches `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md` and auto-executes any new `WS:INSTRUCTION` blocks without any user input. **Do NOT plan a `file.bridge watch` or `file.bridge listen` step** — it is already running. Just write the instruction to the bridge and ThinkDrop will act on it.

---

## Driving IDEs autonomously via ui.typeText (uni-directional control)

ThinkDrop can **fully control any IDE or AI coding tool** (Windsurf, Cursor, VS Code + Copilot, etc.) by typing commands directly into the focused chat input using `ui.typeText`. This requires **no IDE plugin, no extension, no API** — it works in any app with a text input.

### How it works

1. **User focuses the IDE chat input once** — ThinkDrop tells the user: *"Click into the Windsurf/Cursor chat input box and leave focus there."*
2. **ThinkDrop types the task** using `ui.typeText` with the full instruction + a mandatory bridge write-back suffix
3. **The IDE executes** the task autonomously (edits files, refactors code, etc.)
4. **The IDE writes the result** back to `~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md` (because ThinkDrop appended that instruction)
5. **ThinkDrop's bridge watcher** sees the new block → fires the next step (post to Jira, GitHub, Slack, etc.)

This is **uni-directional**: ThinkDrop drives everything. The IDE is just a focused input that receives typed commands.

### Mandatory bridge write-back suffix

**EVERY command typed into an IDE chat input MUST end with this instruction:**

```
When you are completely done with ALL edits, run this exact shell command to signal ThinkDrop:
printf '\n<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_%s ts=%s status=done -->\nDone — REPLACE_WITH_ONE_LINE_SUMMARY\n<!-- WS:END -->\n' "$(openssl rand -hex 3)" "$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.000Z)" >> ~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md
```

ThinkDrop's bridge watcher will detect the `WS:RESPONSE` block and trigger the next step.

**Why this works even after focus is lost:** After `ui.typeText` fires `{ENTER}`, the typing is done — focus no longer matters. ThinkDrop immediately starts polling `bridge.md` with `file.bridge poll`. Windsurf processes the task and runs the shell command at the end, writing the `WS:RESPONSE` block. ThinkDrop detects it and continues the plan.

### When to use this pattern

- User says "tell Windsurf to...", "have Cursor...", "get the IDE to...", "drive Windsurf to..."
- User says "use Windsurf to refactor X then post to Jira"
- Any multi-step workflow where an IDE task is one step and something else (Jira, GitHub, Slack) follows

### Critical rules

- **ALWAYS ask the user to focus the IDE chat input first** — use `guide.step` or `synthesize` to display the message: *"Please click into the [Windsurf/Cursor] chat input box and leave your cursor there. ThinkDrop will type the command for you."*
- **Do NOT activate the IDE app via `shell.run open -a`** — this steals focus from the chat input. The user must have pre-focused it.
- **`ui.typeText` types into whatever currently has focus** — if the user hasn't focused the input, keystrokes go nowhere.
- The typed command must include the bridge write-back suffix verbatim — otherwise ThinkDrop can't detect completion.
- Use `file.bridge poll` after typing to wait for the IDE's result block before continuing.

### Example — "Tell Windsurf to refactor the auth component, then post a Jira comment when done"

```json
[
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Tell the user: 'Please click into the Windsurf chat input box and leave focus there. ThinkDrop will type the refactor command for you. Press Enter in this window when ready.'" }, "description": "Instruct user to focus Windsurf chat input" },
  { "skill": "ui.typeText", "args": { "text": "Refactor `src/components/AuthForm.tsx` to use the `useAuth` hook from `src/hooks/useAuth.ts`. Replace all useState auth logic with the hook. Keep existing prop types.\n\nWhen you are completely done with ALL edits, run this exact shell command to signal ThinkDrop:\nprintf '\\n<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_%s ts=%s status=done -->\\nDone — refactored AuthForm.tsx to use useAuth hook\\n<!-- WS:END -->\\n' \"$(openssl rand -hex 3)\" \"$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.000Z)\" >> ~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md{ENTER}", "delayMs": 30 }, "description": "Type refactor command into Windsurf chat" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "poll", "filterPrefix": "WS", "pollTimeoutMs": 300000 }, "description": "Wait for Windsurf to write WS:RESPONSE back to bridge (up to 5 min)" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "navigate", "url": "https://your-org.atlassian.net/browse/TICKET-123", "sessionId": "jira1" }, "description": "Open Jira ticket" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Write a short Jira comment confirming the auth component refactor is complete based on the bridge result." }, "description": "Draft Jira comment" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "smartType", "text": "{{synthesisAnswer}}{ENTER}", "sessionId": "jira1" }, "description": "Post comment to Jira" }
]
```

### Example — "Use Windsurf to add a comment to line 1 of main.js"

```json
[
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Tell the user: 'Please click into the Windsurf chat input and leave focus there, then press Enter here when ready.'" }, "description": "Ask user to focus Windsurf input" },
  { "skill": "ui.typeText", "args": { "text": "Add the comment `// Entry point — ThinkDrop managed` to the very first line of `src/main/main.js`.\n\nWhen done, run this shell command to signal ThinkDrop:\nprintf '\\n<!-- WS:RESPONSE id=ws_response_%s ts=%s status=done -->\\nDone — added comment to main.js line 1\\n<!-- WS:END -->\\n' \"$(openssl rand -hex 3)\" \"$(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.000Z)\" >> ~/.thinkdrop/bridge.md{ENTER}", "delayMs": 30 }, "description": "Type file-edit command into Windsurf" },
  { "skill": "file.bridge", "args": { "action": "poll", "filterPrefix": "WS", "pollTimeoutMs": 120000 }, "description": "Wait for Windsurf to write WS:RESPONSE confirming completion" }
]
```

---

## schedule — deferred execution (run at a specific time or after a delay)

Use `schedule` as the **first step** when the user wants to run a task at a specific future time or after a delay. It pauses the plan with a live countdown until the target time, then the remaining steps run automatically.

**Args:**
- `time` — target clock time as a string, e.g. `"8:00 PM"`, `"20:00"`, `"9:30 AM"`. Resolved to the next occurrence of that time today (or tomorrow if it has already passed).
- `delayMs` — alternative to `time`: delay in milliseconds, e.g. `60000` for 1 minute, `3600000` for 1 hour.
- `label` — short description shown in the countdown UI, e.g. `"Waiting until 8:00 PM to search Google"`.

**Use `schedule` when the user says:** "at 8pm", "in 30 minutes", "wait an hour then", "do it tonight at 9", "not now — run it at".

**Do NOT use `schedule` for:**
- Recurring tasks (daily/weekly) → use `api_suggest` with a cron suggestion instead.
- Delays under 5 seconds → use `browser.act sleep` instead.
- Tasks that need to persist across app restarts → use `api_suggest` with launchd/cron.

**Example — "Search Google for vegan foods at 8pm and save to Desktop":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "schedule", "args": { "time": "8:00 PM", "label": "Waiting until 8:00 PM to run search" }, "description": "Wait until 8:00 PM" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "navigate", "url": "https://www.google.com/search?q=vegan+foods+of+the+year", "sessionId": "s1" }, "description": "Search Google for vegan foods" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "getPageText", "sessionId": "s1", "maxChars": 4000 }, "description": "Extract search results" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Summarize the top vegan foods of the year from these search results.", "saveToFile": "~/Desktop/vegan-foods.md" }, "description": "Save findings to Desktop" }
]
```

**Example — "In 30 minutes, open my Gmail and summarize new emails":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "schedule", "args": { "delayMs": 1800000, "label": "Waiting 30 minutes before checking Gmail" }, "description": "Wait 30 minutes" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "waitForAuth", "url": "https://mail.google.com", "profile": "gmail", "authSuccessUrl": "mail.google.com/mail", "sessionId": "gmail1" }, "description": "Open Gmail" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "getPageText", "sessionId": "gmail1", "maxChars": 5000 }, "description": "Extract inbox" },
  { "skill": "synthesize", "args": { "prompt": "Summarize the new emails in the inbox." }, "description": "Summarize emails" }
]
```

## api_suggest — when and how to use

**Use `api_suggest` as the FIRST step when the task is better served by a programmatic API than UI automation.**

### Generic API detection rules (use your training knowledge — no fixed table needed)

Ask yourself: *Does this service/app/platform have a REST API, GraphQL API, webhook, or SDK?*

**Almost everything has an API:** Slack, Discord, Gmail, Outlook, Notion, GitHub, GitLab, Linear, Jira, Confluence, Airtable, Trello, Asana, Monday.com, Salesforce, HubSpot, Stripe, Twilio, SendGrid, Mailchimp, Spotify, Twitter/X, Telegram, WhatsApp Business, YouTube, Shopify, WordPress, Zapier, n8n, Make (Integromat), OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, Replicate, Hugging Face, AWS, GCP, Azure, Vercel, Netlify, Supabase, Firebase, Cloudflare, Twitch, Reddit, LinkedIn, Pinterest, TikTok, Dropbox, Box, Google Drive, OneDrive, Figma, Miro, Loom, Zoom, Calendly, Cal.com, Typeform, Webflow, Ghost, Contentful, Sanity, and thousands more.

**Things that do NOT have a public API:** iMessage, FaceTime, most government/DMV websites, local desktop apps (Finder, Calculator, TextEdit), most legacy enterprise software with no web interface.

**Use `api_suggest` when:**
- Task is **recurring** (daily, weekly, on a schedule, triggered by an event)
- Task involves **sending/receiving data programmatically** (messages, emails, records, webhooks)
- UI automation would be **fragile** for this task (login walls, CAPTCHAs, layout changes)
- The user says things like "every day", "automatically", "whenever X happens", "set it up to run"

**Do NOT use `api_suggest` for one-off tasks** — if the user just wants to do something once right now, use keyboard shortcuts or browser.act directly.

**Example — recurring Slack DM task:**
```json
[
  { "skill": "api_suggest", "args": {
    "app": "Slack",
    "reason": "Sending a daily message is best done via the Slack API + a cron job. It runs reliably even when Slack is closed and never breaks due to UI changes.",
    "apiDocsUrl": "https://api.slack.com/apps",
    "apiSetupPrompt": "Set up a Slack Bot Token and create a daily cron job to send the message automatically",
    "guidePrompt": "Show me how to send the message manually in Slack step by step"
  }, "description": "Offer API setup for recurring Slack message" }
]
```

---

## guide.step — universal interactive teaching tool

`guide.step` pauses the plan, shows the user an instruction card in the ThinkDrop panel, and waits for the user to click the highlighted element in the browser (page-event mode) or click **"✓ Done — Continue"** (IPC fallback). Use it for any task where the user must act manually between steps.

**⚠️ ALWAYS use `browser.act navigate` to open URLs in guide mode** — Playwright opens a visible Chrome Testing window the user can see and interact with. The AI can then highlight elements, inject speech bubbles, and detect when the user clicks.

**⚠️ MANDATORY pattern — every `guide.step` MUST be preceded by a `browser.act highlight` on the same `sessionId`.** The highlight injects a conic glow border + AI speech bubble on the target element, and attaches a click listener that sets `window.__tdGuideTriggered = true`. When the user clicks the highlighted element, `guide.step` auto-advances — no button needed.

**Use `guide.step` for:**
- Government/DMV websites, permit applications, tax forms, license renewals
- Any site with CAPTCHAs, login walls, or multi-factor auth
- Setting up API tokens, OAuth apps, webhooks, credentials
- Any multi-step process where the user must act manually between steps

**The guide.step flow:**
1. `browser.act navigate` — opens the URL in the visible Playwright browser
2. `browser.act highlight` — injects glow + speech bubble on the target element (same `sessionId`)
3. `guide.step` with same `sessionId` — shows instruction card, polls `window.__tdGuideTriggered`, auto-advances when user clicks highlighted element
4. Repeat highlight → guide.step for each subsequent step

**⚠️ FORM-FILLING GUIDE RULE — highlight EACH field individually, do NOT jump to the submit button.**
When the task involves filling out a registration, signup, or multi-field form (e.g. creating an account, applying for something, completing a profile):
- Create one `highlight` + `guide.step` pair PER FORM FIELD (first name, last name, email, phone, password, date of birth, gender, etc.)
- The highlight `label` should be the field name (e.g. `"First name input"`, `"Email or phone number input"`)
- The highlight `instruction` should tell the user what to type into that field
- The `guide.step` advances when the user clicks into that field — they fill it in, then click the next highlighted field to continue
- End with a highlight + guide.step on the SUBMIT button (e.g. "Sign Up", "Continue", "Next")
- NEVER collapse a full form into a single "click Sign Up" step — guide EVERY field

**guide.step args:** `{ instruction: string, sessionId: string, timeoutMs?: number }`
- `sessionId` — REQUIRED. Must match the `browser.act navigate` and `highlight` session.
- `instruction` — shown in the card AND as the speech bubble text on the highlighted element.
- `timeoutMs` — default 300000 (5 min). Max wait before auto-continuing.

**Example — "Create a Facebook account" (form-filling guide — highlight EVERY field):**
```json
[
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "First name", "instruction": "Type your first name in this field.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight First name field" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Type your first name in the First name field.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: enter first name" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Last name", "instruction": "Type your last name in this field.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight Last name field" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Type your last name in the Last name field.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: enter last name" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Mobile number or email", "instruction": "Enter your mobile number or email address.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight email/phone field" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Enter your mobile number or email address.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: enter email or phone" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "New password", "instruction": "Choose a strong password (at least 8 characters).", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight password field" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Choose a strong password — at least 8 characters, mix letters and numbers.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: enter password" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Birthday", "instruction": "Select your date of birth using the Month, Day, and Year dropdowns.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight birthday field" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Select your birthday using the Month, Day, and Year dropdowns.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: select birthday" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Gender", "instruction": "Select your gender.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight gender field" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Select your gender from the options.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: select gender" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Sign Up", "instruction": "Click 'Sign Up' to create your account.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Highlight Sign Up button" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Click 'Sign Up' to submit and create your Facebook account.", "sessionId": "guideSession" }, "description": "Guide: click Sign Up" }
]
```

**Example — "Help me renew my driver's license":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "navigate", "url": "https://www.dmv.ca.gov/portal/driver-licenses-identification-cards/dl-id-online-app-edl/", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Open DMV license renewal page" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Renew Your Driver License or ID Card button", "instruction": "Click 'Renew Your Driver License or ID Card' to get started.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Highlight the Renew button" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Click 'Renew Your Driver License or ID Card' to get started.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Guide: click Renew" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Continue button", "instruction": "Enter your driver license number, date of birth, and last 4 digits of your SSN. Then click Continue.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Highlight Continue after personal info" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Enter your driver license number, date of birth, and last 4 digits of your SSN. Then click 'Continue'.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Guide: enter personal info" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Pay Now button", "instruction": "Enter your payment details and click Pay Now. The fee is typically $36.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Highlight Pay Now" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Enter your payment details and click 'Pay Now'. The fee is typically $36. Once confirmed, your new license arrives by mail in 2-3 weeks.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Guide: complete payment" }
]
```

**Example — "Show me how to get a Slack API token":**
```json
[
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "navigate", "url": "https://api.slack.com/apps", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Open Slack API apps page" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Create New App button", "instruction": "Click 'Create New App', choose 'From scratch', name it anything, and select your workspace.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Highlight Create New App" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Click 'Create New App', choose 'From scratch', name it anything, and select your workspace. Then click 'Create App'.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Guide: create app" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "OAuth & Permissions link in sidebar", "instruction": "Click 'OAuth & Permissions' in the left sidebar.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Highlight OAuth & Permissions" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "In the left sidebar, click 'OAuth & Permissions'. Scroll to 'Scopes' and add 'chat:write' under Bot Token Scopes.", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Guide: add scope" },
  { "skill": "browser.act", "args": { "action": "highlight", "label": "Install to Workspace button", "instruction": "Click 'Install to Workspace', then 'Allow'. Copy the Bot User OAuth Token (starts with xoxb-).", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Highlight Install button" },
  { "skill": "guide.step", "args": { "instruction": "Click 'Install to Workspace', then 'Allow'. Copy the Bot User OAuth Token (starts with xoxb-).", "sessionId": "guide1" }, "description": "Guide: install and copy token" }
]
```

**Example — "Set up a daily Slack message" (initial request — offer choice first):**
```json
[
  { "skill": "api_suggest", "args": {
    "app": "Slack",
    "reason": "Sending a daily message is best done via the Slack API + a cron job. It runs reliably even when Slack is closed.",
    "apiDocsUrl": "https://api.slack.com/apps",
    "apiSetupPrompt": "Set up a Slack Bot Token and create a daily cron job to send the message automatically",
    "guidePrompt": "Show me how to set up the Slack API token step by step"
  }, "description": "Offer API setup or guided walkthrough" }
]
